    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1916-01-29T13:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1916-01-29T13:00:00-05:00" n="204"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d204">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 763.72/2363</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Germany</hi> (<persName corresp="#p_GJW1"
                        type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Gerard</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram]</seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Berlin</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1916-01-29T19:00:00+01:00">
                            <hi rend="italic">January 29, 1916, 7 p. m.</hi>
                        </date>
                        <lb/> [<hi rend="italic">Received January 30, 5.15 p. m.</hi>]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>3406. <persName corresp="#p_ZAFM1">Zimmermann</persName> here at lunch to-day. He
                    had long talk with <persName corresp="#p_HEM1">Colonel House</persName>. Before
                    that he talked to me and said he had just received the <hi rend="italic"
                        >Lusitania</hi> note proposed by <persName corresp="#p_BJHACV1"
                        >Bernstorff</persName>; that <persName corresp="#p_BJHACV1"
                        >Bernstorff</persName> himself had cabled that he knew the German Government
                    would not accept it. <persName corresp="#p_ZAFM1">Zimmermann</persName> further
                    stated that if Germany had war with America they then could have an effective
                    submarine blockade of England and could sink ships without warning, and that
                    they had plenty of new submarines. He said that he was sure the <persName
                        corresp="#p_BJHACV1">Bernstorff</persName> proposition would not be accepted
                    here on account of public opinion. I think that with modifications <persName
                        corresp="#p_BJHACV1">Bernstorff</persName> note would be accepted.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_GJW1">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Gerard</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
